Here's the honest answer: **don't build auth yourself. Use a managed provider.**

## The fastest path that scales

**Pick one of these hosted auth providers:**

| Provider | Why it works | Cost at your size |
|----------|-------------|-------------------|
| **Clerk** | Best DX, fastest to integrate, good docs | Free tier covers you |
| **Auth0** | Battle-tested, most flexible | Free up to 7,500 MAU |
| **Supabase Auth** | Great if you're already on Supabase | Free tier generous |
| **Firebase Auth** | Good if you're in GCP | Free for most auth methods |

**My pick for a 4-person startup: Clerk or Auth0.** Clerk if you want speed, Auth0 if you want maximum flexibility later.

## What this looks like concretely

**1. Auth provider issues JWTs.** Your frontend redirects to their login page (or uses their embedded component). They handle passwords, OAuth, MFA, account recovery - all the stuff that will absolutely bite you if you build it yourself.

**2. Your API validates JWTs.** This is the only part you write:

```ts
// middleware.ts - that's basically it
import { verifyToken } from '@clerk/backend'; // or jose, jsonwebtoken, etc.

async function authMiddleware(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace('Bearer ', '');
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'No token' });

  try {
    const payload = await verifyToken(token, {
      secretKey: process.env.AUTH_SECRET_KEY,
    });
    req.userId = payload.sub;
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid token' });
  }
}
```

**3. Add authorization (who can do what) as a thin layer on top:**

```ts
// Simple role check - don't over-engineer this yet
function requireRole(role: string) {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    if (req.user.role !== role) return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
    next();
  };
}
```

## What NOT to do

- **Don't roll your own password hashing/storage.** You will get it wrong. Everyone does.
- **Don't use API keys as your only auth.** Fine for service-to-service, not for user-facing.
- **Don't build session management from scratch.** It's a solved problem.
- **Don't add OAuth yourself.** Each provider has quirks. Let the auth service eat that complexity.
- **Don't skip HTTPS.** Non-negotiable. Use it everywhere, even internal APIs.

## The things you SHOULD build yourself

- **Authorization logic** (who can access what resources) - this is your business logic, no one else can own it
- **API rate limiting** - a simple token bucket or use something like `express-rate-limit`
- **Audit logging** - log who did what, when. You'll want this for debugging and compliance

## Timeline

For a 4-person team with an existing API:

- **Day 1:** Sign up for auth provider, integrate their SDK, protect one endpoint
- **Day 2:** Roll it out to all endpoints, add role-based checks where needed
- **Day 3:** Add rate limiting, audit logging, test the error paths

Three days to auth that won't embarrass you. Spending more time than that means you're building something you shouldn't be.

