Two separate problems, two targeted fixes:

## 1. Out-of-order messages

Kafka guarantees ordering **per partition**. If messages arrive out of order, your related messages are landing on different partitions.

**Fix:** Set a consistent partition key on your producer so related messages always hit the same partition.

```java
// Before: round-robin across partitions
producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("events", event));

// After: key by the entity that needs ordering
producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("events", order.getId(), event));
```

Pick the key that represents your ordering boundary - usually an entity ID (order ID, user ID, account ID). All events for that entity go to the same partition, Kafka handles the rest.

## 2. Duplicate processing

Kafka gives you **at-least-once** delivery by default. Consumer crashes after processing but before committing the offset? That message gets redelivered.

**Fix:** Make your consumer idempotent. Cheapest approach - track processed message IDs:

```java
// Simple idempotency check before processing
String messageId = record.headers().lastHeader("message-id").value();

// Upsert into a dedup table (or Redis set, whatever you already have)
boolean alreadyProcessed = dedup.putIfAbsent(messageId, true) != null;
if (alreadyProcessed) {
    log.info("Skipping duplicate: {}", messageId);
    return;
}

processEvent(record);
```

If your processing is a database write, you can skip the separate dedup store and just make the write itself idempotent:

```sql
-- Natural idempotency via upsert
INSERT INTO results (event_id, payload, processed_at)
VALUES (?, ?, NOW())
ON CONFLICT (event_id) DO NOTHING;
```

## What NOT to do

- **Don't switch to exactly-once semantics** (`enable.idempotence` + transactions) unless you're staying entirely within Kafka. It doesn't extend to your downstream DB/API calls, so you still need application-level idempotency anyway.
- **Don't drop to a single partition** for global ordering. It kills throughput. Order within an entity, not globally.
- **Don't manually commit offsets after every message.** It reduces duplicates slightly but tanks performance and doesn't eliminate them (crash between process and commit is still possible).

Both fixes are producer/consumer config + a few lines of code. No new infrastructure, no rearchitecture.
